<p>Portion 11:</p>
<p>This brings us to the second form of relativism which is societal 
relativism. Societal relativism suggests that morality is created not by
 the individual but, instead, by society at large. There are as many 
forms of societal relativism as there are forms of government, but they 
all basically boil down to the same concept. Society has the strength 
necessary to impose rule. Whether the society has a democratic 
government or a dictatorship at least there’s a standard outside of 
one’s self that we can adhere to. This means that the government, of any
 type, gets to decide what’s moral and what’s not moral for their 
citizens. A societal relativist might say, "when in Rome, it is moral to
 do as the Romans do."<br>
This is similar to saying that the CEO, COO, and CIO of your company can
 decide for you and all the other employees in your company what’s moral
 or immoral. Are we sure we want to give other humans that kind of 
power? In this case it would almost universally be considered “wrong” to
 rise up against them at any time. Is it true that it would always be 
wrong to object to company practices just because the owner of your 
company says it’s wrong to object?<br>
The pitfalls of this belief are very similar to individual relativism. 
Because no objective right and wrong exists, no particular war can be 
said to be just or unjust. No particular mode of culture can be said to 
be humane or inhumane. Under this banner, the actions of every dictator 
who ever lived cannot be considered just or unjust. Genocide carried out
 by any nation or collective is simply a logical or illogical solution 
to their problems.<br>
I’d like you to consider this: what percentage of society has to agree 
before something can be considered moral or immoral? How large would the
 society have to be? Is two people enough or would there need to be 
others? How many more would be needed? I'm sure most of us can agree 
that the actions of Nazi Germany were extremely immoral. Did they have 
enough people to constitute a society?<br>
If we ask these questions, we can see that societies are made up of 
individuals. Which means that societal relativism breaks back down into 
individual relativism which breaks down into the non-existence of 
morality. Although there are people who may try to use relativistic 
ideas as an escape from choosing between a belief that morality exists 
or a belief that morality does not exist, the use of relativistic ideas 
becomes part of the choice itself. Relativism in all of its theories and
 forms is a subcategory of belief in the non-existence of morality.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="Message_messageMetadataContainer__nBPq7"><span class="Message_messageMetadataText__FxY5_">5:16 AM</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_chatMessage__xkgHx" data-complete="true" id="message-230686417877"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_leftSideMessageHeader__5CfdD"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_headerWrapper__EpVkV"><div class="BotMessageHeader_wrapper__gvvdw"><a class="BotHeader_title__cURS_" target="_blank" href=""><div class="Avatar_root__rwLF0 Avatar_rounded__qlug0 Avatar_xx-sm__hwmu_" data-pdl-avatar=""><img alt="Bot image for BotORFQ3TYM2O" data-deleted="true" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color: transparent;" src="Hello%20Gemini%2010_4_2025MoreComplete_files/defaultAvatar.7e5c73d2.png"></div><div class="BotHeader_textContainer__kVf_I"><p>BotORFQ3TYM2O</p></div></a></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageRow__DHlnq"><div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageWrapper__4Ugd6"><div class="Message_rowWithFooter__FShU6"><div class="Message_row__ug_UU"><div class="Message_messageBubbleWrapper__sEq8z"><div class="Message_leftSideMessageBubble__VPdk6"><div class="Message_messageTextContainer__w64Sc"><div class="Message_selectableText__SQ8WH"><div class="Markdown_markdownContainer__Tz3HQ"><div class="Prose_prose__7AjXb Prose_presets_prose__H9VRM Prose_presets_theme-hi-contrast__LQyM9"><p><em>I
