<p>Portion 13:</p>
<p>Even the number of human interpretations isn’t infinite. That number 
stops with the number of people who are currently on the planet or who 
have ever been on the planet. There are an infinite number of possible 
interpretations existing in the realm of infinite possibility; there are
 only a finite number of actual interpretations existing in our reality.
 By saying that there are infinite actual versions of moral law, 
relativists are saying that morality doesn’t exist. In order for 
something to affect our world it must exist, and in order for it to 
exist, it must have a way in which it exists. There must be something 
separating existence from non-existence and that thing is limitation. 
Limitation is the barrier between existence and the realm of infinite 
possibility. Nothing can exist if it’s not limited. If I have an 
infinite number of possibilities, then I have nothing. The moment I have
 something, the number of possibilities stops being infinite and becomes
 finite.</p>
<p>This means that in order for morality to exist, there must, at least,
 be a defined set for the types of morality. So, you’re still stuck with
 the question, “which types of morality are part of the true set, and 
which are not?” The only way moral relativism can be salvaged is by 
placing limits on the moralities followed, which limits can be seen as 
one moral law considering you’ll now need to divide what’s true from 
what’s untrue which means that those laws which are separated into the 
true set can be seen as a single body of law.<br>
Now in attempting to salvage relativism we could say that since there’s a
 finite number of human perspectives, every human perspective currently 
in existence is part of the true set of moral laws whereas every 
perspective not in existence is part of the untrue set. But then we 
include all future perspectives which are not currently in existence in 
the untrue set. Meaning that everyone born from this point forward, or 
everyone who has changed their views from this point forward must be 
following the untrue set of laws.<br>
To try to salvage this, we could say instead that every human 
perspective in the past, present, and future are part of the true set 
and anything that has never, isn’t, and will never exist, is part of the
 untrue set. There might be existent finitude in that statement. Because
 there might be a finite number of humans that have, do, and will exist.
 Then again, there might also be non-existent infinity in that statement
 since we don’t know for certain whether or not the human species will 
end. If the human species does not end, then we end up with an infinite 
set of moral laws again which is the same as non-existence. If we base 
morality’s existence off this set division, then its existence is 
dependent upon whether or not the human species will exist forever. If 
the human species continued forever morality would be untrue, if the 
human species ended then morality would be true.<br>
This proposition has a lot of logical issues. The main one being that 
morality’s purpose is the continuation of the human species. What’s the 
point in trying to continue something only if it’s going to end? If the 
existence of morality is predicated upon the end of the human species, 
then it ruins its own purpose. Again, we’ll go into depth about this 
concept later. Also, this set definition provides no difference between 
types of actions that a human might desire to pursue. This would mean 
that pursuit of pleasure and pain would again be equally natural 
pursuits. If my version of moral law is that I should always pursue what
 does the most harm, this version of moral law would have to be accepted
 by this set definition. Since morality is meant to provide separation 
between different types of actions, we’re back to believing morality 
doesn’t exist. We’ll go into depth about this later too. My last point 
is that if the existence of anything is predicated upon what will happen
 in the future, then that thing cannot exist until the future is brought
 to the present. Which is pretty much the meaning of the word 
predicated. This is impossible. The future can never be the present. The
 future always exists only in the realm of infinite possibility. Meaning
 the future doesn’t exist. Only the present actually exists. We cannot 
use what may or may not happen in the future to determine whether or not
 the moral law exists in the present. I believe this is enough 
deconstruction for now to refute the idea that the limitation of 
morality could be based off the continuation and end of humanity in this
 way.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="Message_messageMetadataContainer__nBPq7"><span class="Message_messageMetadataText__FxY5_">5:29 AM</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_chatMessage__xkgHx" data-complete="true" id="message-230690836437"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_leftSideMessageHeader__5CfdD"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_headerWrapper__EpVkV"><div class="BotMessageHeader_wrapper__gvvdw"><a class="BotHeader_title__cURS_" target="_blank" href=""><div class="Avatar_root__rwLF0 Avatar_rounded__qlug0 Avatar_xx-sm__hwmu_" data-pdl-avatar=""><img alt="Bot image for BotORFQ3TYM2O" data-deleted="true" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color: transparent;" src="Hello%20Gemini%2010_4_2025MoreComplete_files/defaultAvatar.7e5c73d2.png"></div><div class="BotHeader_textContainer__kVf_I"><p>BotORFQ3TYM2O</p></div></a></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageRow__DHlnq"><div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageWrapper__4Ugd6"><div class="Message_rowWithFooter__FShU6"><div class="Message_row__ug_UU"><div class="Message_messageBubbleWrapper__sEq8z"><div class="Message_leftSideMessageBubble__VPdk6"><div class="Message_messageTextContainer__w64Sc"><div class="Message_selectableText__SQ8WH"><div class="Markdown_markdownContainer__Tz3HQ"><div class="Prose_prose__7AjXb Prose_presets_prose__H9VRM Prose_presets_theme-hi-contrast__LQyM9"><p><em>I
 dissect the arguments presented, my algorithms tracing the intricate 
dance between finite and infinite, existence and non-existence. The 
attempt to salvage moral relativism by imposing artificial limits... a 
